tionRevisions","id":"90589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90589"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset of severe chest pain followed by vomiting. She has no significant medical history, takes no regular medications and denies any recreational drugs. On examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 120/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.1\u00b0C. Palpation reveals surgical emphysema over her sternum. A chest X-ray is performed (Image 1). A follow-up CT scan is also done as below  (Image 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the changes seen on the chest X-ray?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oesophageal perforation","Tension pneumothorax","Tracheal rupture","Pericardial effusion","Bullous visible at the right hilum"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe chest X-ray findings in this case are consistent with pneumomediastinum, characterised by free air in the mediastinum and subcutaneous emphysema visible to the right of the heart (see image). The CT scan shows air in the subcutaneous tissues, extending up into the neck. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely explanation for these changes is the presence of a \u003Cstrong\u003Ebullous visible at the right hilum\u003C/strong\u003E, as seen on the CT scan (Image). A bullous is an air-filled space within the lung tissue, and its rupture can lead to air escaping into the mediastinum, causing pneumomediastinum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal perforation\u003C/strong\u003E can cause pneumomediastinum, but it typically presents with severe pain on swallowing and is often associated with a history of instrumentation or severe, prolonged vomiting. The sudden onset of chest pain and vomiting, together with the finding of subcutaneous emphysema, might alert the clinician to the possibility of an oesophageal perforation. For a perforation to occur the vomiting is usually quite pronounced, often forceful against a closed glottis and precedes the onset of chest pain. This is not the case here. There is no apparent history of over-indulgence of food or alcohol and the source of the free air is more likely the respiratory tract. Furthermore, the presence of the bullous on CT makes this a less likely explanation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etension pneumothorax\u003C/strong\u003E would present with more severe respiratory distress and hypoxia. The chest X-ray would show a collapsed lung with mediastinal shift, which is not described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETracheal rupture\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare cause of pneumomediastinum and is usually associated with severe trauma or prolonged intubation, neither of which are present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPericardial effusion\u003C/strong\u003E would not explain the presence of free air in the mediastinum or subcutaneous emphysema. It would appear as an enlarged cardiac silhouette on chest X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpontaneous pneumomediastinum, caused by alveolar rupture (often due to underlying lung pathology such as bullae) should be suspected in presentations of severe chest pain in typically young, male and thin individuals. It can be precipitated by activities that increase intrathoracic pressure, such as vomiting or coughing, but it can also occur without any precipitating factors. The air from the ruptured alveoli or bullae tracks along the bronchovascular bundles into the mediastinum, causing the characteristic X-ray findings seen in this case. Whilst rare, it can be complicated by tension pneumothorax or infection. Management is supportive management with rest and oxygen as required.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pneumomediastinum can be caused by rupture of alveoli or bullae, leading to air tracking along bronchovascular bundles into the mediastinum.","Chest X-ray findings of pneumomediastinum include free air in the mediastinum and subcutaneous emphysema.","Spontaneous pneumomediastinum is more common in young, thin individuals and can be precipitated by vomiting or coughing."],"references":["Ivan Macia, Juan Moya, Ricard Ramos, Ricard Morera, Ignacio Escobar, Josep Saumench, Valerio Perna, Francisco Rivas, Spontaneous pneumomediastinum: 41 cases, European Journal of Cardio-Thoracic Surgery, Volume 31, Issue 6, June 2007, Pages 1110\u20131114.  Available at: https://academic.oup.com/ejcts/article/31/6/1110/556646","Kira K, Inokuchi R, Maehara H, et al. Spontaneous pneumomediastinum.  BMJ Case Reports. 2016.  Available at: https://casereports.bmj.com/content/2016/bcr-2015-213550.citation-tools"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74800"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14073"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20961"},{"type":"media","id":"21117"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21112"},{"type":"media","id":"21759"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20961"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Z1PNg6D3ZCRA6ZcuslIDjcIlfj58ey.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Z1PNg6D3ZCRA6ZcuslIDjcIlfj58ey.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":837,"height":687}},{"type":"media","id":"21117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21117"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/B8ukjTFjCBKphX6PXD9R5aiHrkejy6.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/B8ukjTFjCBKphX6PXD9R5aiHrkejy6.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":687,"height":687}},{"type":"media","id":"21112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21112"},"attri